WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Teacher: Good afternoon everyone! I'm excited about today's lesson. We're going to do a debate about renewable energy!

00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:25.000
Teacher: First, let's review. What types of renewable energy have you heard of? Call them out!

00:00:25.500 --> 00:00:28.000
Student 1: Solar power!

00:00:28.500 --> 00:00:31.000
Student 2: Wind turbines!

00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:34.000
Student 3: Hydroelectric!

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:37.000
Student 4: Geothermal?

00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:42.000
Student 5: Nuclear... wait, is that renewable?

00:00:42.500 --> 00:00:55.000
Teacher: Great question, Michael! Nuclear is actually a debate itself. It's low-carbon but the fuel isn't technically renewable. What do you all think?

00:00:55.500 --> 00:01:05.000
Student 2: I think it counts because it doesn't pollute the air like coal.

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:15.000
Student 6: But what about the nuclear waste? That's really dangerous.

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:25.000
Student 1: My dad works at a solar company. He says solar is getting cheaper every year.

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:35.000
Teacher: Excellent points from everyone! You're already in debate mode. Now let's organize this.

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:50.000
Teacher: I'm dividing you into four groups. Each group will argue for a different energy source: solar, wind, hydro, or nuclear.

00:01:50.500 --> 00:02:00.000
Student 3: Can we pick which one we want to argue for?

00:02:00.500 --> 00:02:15.000
Teacher: Actually, I'm going to assign them randomly. Part of learning is arguing for positions you might not initially agree with.

00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:25.000
Student 4: That's hard but kind of cool.

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:45.000
Teacher: You have 15 minutes to prepare your arguments. Use the fact sheets I'm handing out, and you can also use the tablets to research.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:03:30.000
[Group Discussion and Research]

00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:45.000
Student 7: Teacher, we found out that Denmark gets over 40% of its electricity from wind!

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:55.000
Teacher: Fantastic research! Make sure to use that statistic in your argument.

00:03:55.500 --> 00:04:05.000
Student 5: Our group wants to know - can we mention the disadvantages of other energy sources?

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:20.000
Teacher: Absolutely! A good debate addresses counterarguments. Just make sure you're also highlighting your source's strengths.

00:04:20.500 --> 00:04:45.000
[More Group Discussion]

00:04:45.500 --> 00:05:00.000
Teacher: Okay, time's up! Let's start our debate. Solar team, you're up first. You have 3 minutes.

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:30.000
Student 1: Solar power is the best because the sun is free and it shines everywhere. Germany and China are leading the world in solar panel installation.

00:05:30.500 --> 00:05:45.000
Student 8: Also, solar panels can go on rooftops so you don't need extra land. And the costs have dropped by 90% in the last decade!

00:05:45.500 --> 00:06:00.000
Teacher: Strong opening! Wind team, your rebuttal?

00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:20.000
Student 2: But what happens at night? Or on cloudy days? Wind turbines can work 24/7 as long as there's wind.

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:35.000
Student 3: And offshore wind farms don't take up any land at all!

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:50.000
Teacher: Great points! This is exactly the kind of critical thinking I want to see. Let's hear from the hydro team.

00:06:50.500 --> 00:07:10.000
Student 4: Hydroelectric power is the most reliable. Dams can store water and release it whenever we need electricity.

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:25.000
Student 6: It's also the oldest renewable energy. We've been using it for over 100 years, so we know it works.

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:40.000
Teacher: And nuclear team?

00:07:40.500 --> 00:08:00.000
Student 5: Nuclear produces the most energy with the smallest footprint. One nuclear plant makes as much power as thousands of wind turbines.

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:20.000
Student 7: And France gets 70% of its electricity from nuclear with very low emissions.

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:40.000
Teacher: Wonderful debate everyone! You've all made compelling arguments. For homework, I want you to write a one-page reflection on which energy source YOU think is best and why.

00:08:40.500 --> 00:09:00.000
Student 8: Can we say we think a combination is best?

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:15.000
Teacher: Absolutely! In fact, most experts agree that a mix of renewable sources is the most practical solution. Great critical thinking!

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:30.000
Teacher: I'm really proud of how engaged you all were today. See you tomorrow!
